Neovim editor-side plugin that expands Plover stenography keyset tokens into LSP snippets during insert mode. Plover, driven by the generated `out/plover-keys.json`, types a sentinel-wrapped token like `@@STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT@@` into the buffer; this plugin detects the complete token on `TextChangedI`, deletes it, and expands the corresponding body from `out/snippets.json` via `vim.snippet.expand` (requires Neovim 0.10+, silently no-ops otherwise). All the real work — key/count logic, type-append, tabstop numbering — happens in the TypeScript compiler elsewhere in the repo; this file is purely the runtime consumer of its two JSON outputs.

The `OPEN`/`CLOSE` sentinel constant (`"@@"`) must stay in sync with `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` in `src/snippet.ts` — if they diverge, tokens will type into buffers but never match. Comment explains the sentinel choice: ASCII (so Javelin/Plover can emit it), non-autopairing, and not valid TypeScript syntax, so it can never collide with real code. Because `OPEN == CLOSE`, `token_before_cursor` strips the trailing close fence from the search string *before* scanning for the last open fence, specifically to avoid the closing "@@" being mistaken for an opening one when both markers are identical — this is the one subtle bit of string logic in the file, and rewriting search order would silently break token detection.

`M.setup(opts)` is the sole entry point: merges `opts` into `config` (needs `snippets_path` pointing at `out/snippets.json`; `filetypes` defaults to the four TS/JS variants, empty table means "any buffer"), loads and JSON-decodes the snippets file into module-local `snippets` (keyId → LSP body), and registers autocmds — a `FileType` autocmd for future buffers plus an immediate `attach_buffer()` call for already-open ones. Missing/invalid `snippets_path` or malformed JSON aborts setup via `vim.notify(..., vim.log.levels.ERROR)` and returns early without erroring.

`token_before_cursor()` returns `key, start_col` (0-indexed byte column) for a complete `@@…@@` token ending exactly at the cursor, or `nil` if none — it only recognizes tokens whose close fence is immediately behind the cursor, not tokens elsewhere on the line. `try_expand()` is wired as the `TextChangedI` callback; it deletes the matched token range via `nvim_buf_set_text` and repositions the cursor before calling `vim.snippet.expand`, so any expansion failure would leave the token already deleted. Both `M._try_expand` and `M._token_before_cursor` are exported explicitly for manual invocation/testing, not used elsewhere in normal operation.